 Oracle ($ORCL) shares slipped by 1.5% in pre-market trading on Friday after the business software giant reported fiscal third-quarter results that missed estimates and investment firm Morgan Stanley said the pending Cerner ($CERN) deal provides uncertainty about the company&#39;s outlook. 

Analyst Keith Weiss, who rates Oracle (ORCL) equal weight with an $87-a-share price target, noted that the company is &quot;increasingly optimistic&quot; about its core business due to factors such as valuation and its cloud service. However, Weiss said that it&#39;s impossible to ignore concerns about Oracle&#39;s (ORCL) $28.3 billion Cerner (CERN) acquisition, including that the deal has caused Oracle (ORCL) to tap the brakes on its share buybacks. 

&quot;With share repurchases slowing, [Oracle] will have to sustain topline growth and operational discipline to drive forward [earnings per share] growth,&quot; Weiss wrote in a note to clients, adding that such a situation presents &quot;a change from recent [company] history.&quot;
